SetDescription: The taxonomy for the destiny project to use for the EQWD - prompts for intervention

SetType.SetTypeDescription: The Standard codeset type is used for regular coding such as keywording or data-extraction. This codeset type can contain multiple levels of child codes but cannot contain the special code types "Include" and "Exclude".

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_agreements: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Agreements. Agreements refer to formal commitments or arrangements established to address environmental or climate-related issues. This includes domestic agreements, government or non-state actor commitments, and inter- or transnational agreements. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “climate accords,” “policy frameworks,” or “legally binding commitments.” Include literature discussing the design, implementation, effectiveness, or coordination of such agreements.

Is_this_study_related_to_domestic_agreements: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Domestic Agreements. Domestic agreements refer to legally or politically binding commitments, policies, or regulations established within a country to address climate change, environmental protection, or sustainability goals. These may include national climate laws, emission reduction targets, adaptation plans, inter-agency coordination mechanisms, or resource management frameworks. Relevant studies may focus on policy design, implementation effectiveness, stakeholder engagement, legal frameworks, and alignment with international commitments.

Is_this_study_related_to_economic_instruments: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Economic Instruments. Economic instruments refer to market-based tools and financial mechanisms used to influence behaviour and support climate or environmental objectives. This includes measures such as carbon pricing, emissions trading, subsidies, taxes, direct investments, and financial incentives. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “market mechanisms,” “fiscal measures,” or “financial incentives for mitigation or adaptation.” Include literature discussing the design, implementation, effectiveness, or impact of economic instruments.

Is_this_study_related_to_governance_strategies_and_targets: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Governance, Strategies and Targets. This refers to the systems, processes, and instruments through which climate or environmental policies are formulated, coordinated, and implemented. It includes government administration, institutional structures, expert advice, performance reviews, policy coordination, stakeholder engagement, planning, binding targets, and strategic goal-setting. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “climate governance,” “implementation planning,” or “institutional frameworks.” Include literature discussing the design, function, or effectiveness of governance mechanisms and strategic targets.

Is_this_study_related_to_information_education_and_training: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Information, Education and Training. This refers to activities aimed at increasing public or stakeholder awareness, knowledge, and capacity related to climate or environmental issues. It includes behavioural interventions, education and training programmes, public awareness campaigns, and the collection or dissemination of data and analysis. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “capacity building,” “environmental education,” or “climate awareness initiatives.” Include literature discussing design, implementation, or effectiveness of these efforts.

Is_this_study_related_to_regulatory_instruments: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Regulatory Instruments. Regulatory instruments refer to legally binding rules and mandates used to control or guide behaviour in support of climate or environmental goals. This includes information requirements, labelling requirements, reporting requirements, other regulation, quotas (including tradeable and non-tradeable), regulation on transactions, price controls, time of use pricing, spatial and land-use planning, standards, bans and moratoria, government green procurement rules, intensity standards, product and production standards, rationing, and trade policy. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “mandatory compliance,” “enforced limits,” “planning restrictions,” or “standard-setting.” Include literature discussing the development, implementation, enforcement, or effects of such instruments.

Is_this_study_related_to_nodality: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Nodality. Nodality refers to the use and organisation of information to influence policy and behaviour. This includes knowledge dissemination, capacity building for professionals, demonstration projects, educational curricula, information campaigns, information-based nudges, knowledge platforms, knowledge generation, policy assessments, RD&D (Research, Development, and Demonstration), scientific assessments, and stakeholder engagement. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “informational governance,” “knowledge transfer,” “evidence-based outreach,” or “learning-based interventions.” Include literature that discusses the design, implementation, or impact of these information-based tools and activities.

Is_this_study_related_to_authority: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Authority. Authority refers to the use of formal power or legal mandate by governments or institutions to create and enforce rules, standards, or strategic direction. This includes binding and non-binding regulation, agreements, labelling or certification requirements, policy strategies, quotas, regulation on transactions, reporting requirements, standards, targets, zoning, and framework legislation. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “legal mandates,” “institutional authority,” “policy enforcement,” or “regulatory power.” Include literature discussing the establishment, exercise, or effectiveness of authoritative mechanisms.

Is_this_study_related_to_treasure: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Treasure. Treasure refers to the use of financial resources by the state to influence behaviour and support climate or environmental goals. This includes direct spending, investments in ecosystems, human resources or human capital, and infrastructure; as well as financial instruments such as incentives, grants, risk underwriting, subsidies, taxation, corrective pricing, and tax deductions. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “public finance,” “government expenditure,” or “fiscal policy tools.” Include literature discussing design, implementation, or impact of such financial mechanisms.

Is_this_study_related_to_organisation: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Organisation. Organisation refers to structural and operational arrangements that support the implementation of climate or environmental action. This includes governmental re-organisation and creation of institutions, coordination mechanisms, expert advisory processes and performance reviews, formalising stakeholder engagement, operation and management, conferences and workshops, use of consultants, facilities management, and procurement. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “institutional design,” “organisational capacity,” or “governance support functions.” Include literature discussing the institution development, coordination, or operation of organisational systems.

AttributesList.AttributeName: Governmental re-organisation and creation of institutions
Expert advisory processes and performance reviews

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_technologies_for_adaptation_to_climate_change: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Technologies for Adaptation to Climate Change. This refers to technologies developed or applied to reduce the vulnerability of systems and communities to the impacts of climate change. This includes technologies for managing coastal zones or river basins, water conservation, efficient water supply and use, adapting or protecting infrastructure and their operation, adaptation technologies in agriculture, forestry, livestock, or agroalimentary production, and human health protection. It also includes technologies that indirectly contribute to climate adaptation. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “climate-resilient technologies,” “adaptive infrastructure,” or “technical solutions for climate impacts.” Include literature discussing design, deployment, effectiveness, or integration of such technologies.
AttributesList.AttributeName: Technologies for adaptation to climate change
Water conservation Efficient water supply Efficient water use
Adapting or protecting infrastructure or their operation
Adaptation technologies in agriculture forestry livestock or agroalimentary production
Technologies having an indirect contribution to adaptation to climate change

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_climate_change_mitigation_technologies_related_to_buildings: boolean // Does this record describe a study on climate change mitigation technologies related to buildings. This refers to technologies designed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions from buildings through improvements in energy efficiency, energy management, and the integration of low-carbon solutions. This includes the integration of renewable energy sources in buildings, energy efficient lighting technologies, energy efficient heating, ventilation or air conditioning (HVAC), technologies improving the efficiency of home appliances, energy efficient technologies in elevators, escalators, and moving walkways, technologies for efficient end-user side electric power management and consumption, architectural or constructional elements improving thermal performance, and enabling or indirect mitigation technologies. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-carbon building technologies,” “energy-saving solutions,” or “green building innovations.” Include literature discussing design, adoption, or effectiveness of these technologies.
AttributesList.AttributeName: Climate change mitigation technologies related to buildings
Integration of renewable energy sources in buildings
Energy efficient heating ventilation or air conditioning
Technologies aiming at improving the efficiency of home appliances
Energy efficient technologies in elevators escalators and moving walkways
Technologies for an efficient end-user side electric power management and consumption
Architectural or constructional elements improving the thermal performance of buildings
Enabling technologies or technologies with a potential or indirect contribution to GHG emissions mitigation

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_capture_and_storage_and_sequestration_or_disposal_of_greenhouse_gases: boolean // Does this record describe a study on capture and storage and sequestration or disposal of greenhouse gases. This refers to technologies and processes aimed at capturing greenhouse gas emissions from sources such as power plants or industrial facilities, and subsequently storing, sequestering, or disposing of them to prevent their release into the atmosphere. This includes carbon capture and storage (CCS), direct air capture, and other methods for permanent or long-term removal. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “CO2 removal,” “carbon sequestration,” or “greenhouse gas disposal.” Include literature discussing methods, deployment, effectiveness, or governance of such approaches.
AttributesList.AttributeName: Capture and storage and sequestration or disposal of greenhouse gases
Capture or disposal of greenhouse gases

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_climate_change_mitigation_technologies_in_ict: boolean // Does this record describe a study on climate change mitigation technologies in information and communication technologies (ICT). This refers to technologies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions through improved energy efficiency in ICT systems. This includes energy efficient computing and reducing energy consumption in communication networks. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “green ICT,” “low-power computing,” or “sustainable digital infrastructure.” Include literature discussing the design, implementation, or impact of these technologies.
AttributesList.AttributeName: Climate change mitigation technologies in information and communication technologies [ICT]
Reducing energy consumption in communication networks

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_reduction_of_ghg_emissions_from_energy_generation_transmission_or_distribution: boolean // Does this record describe a study on the reduction of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions related to energy generation, transmission, or distribution. This includes technologies and systems aimed at lowering emissions across the energy supply chain. Relevant areas include energy generation through renewable energy sources, combustion technologies with mitigation potential, energy generation of nuclear origin, efficient power generation, transmission or distribution, production of fuel of non-fossil origin, enabling or indirect mitigation technologies, and other energy conversion or management systems reducing GHG emissions. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-carbon energy systems,” “clean power technologies,” or “energy sector decarbonisation.” Include literature discussing deployment, effectiveness, or innovation in these domains.

Energy generation through renewable energy sources
Technologies for an efficient electrical power generation transmission or distribution

Other energy conversion or management systems reducing GHG emissions

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_climate_change_mitigation_technologies_in_the_production_or_processing_of_goods: boolean // Does this record describe a study on climate change mitigation technologies in the production or processing of goods. This refers to technologies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions in industrial and agricultural production systems. This includes technologies related to metal processing, chemical industry, oil refining and petrochemical industry, processing of minerals, and agriculture, livestock, or agroalimentary industries. It also covers technologies for final product manufacturing, sector-wide mitigation strategies, and enabling technologies with a potential contribution to GHG emissions mitigation. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-emission industrial technologies,” “clean production,” or “industrial decarbonisation.” Include literature discussing development, application, or impact of these technologies.

Technologies relating to oil refining and petrochemical industry
Technologies relating to the processing of minerals
Technologies relating to agriculture livestock or agroalimentary industries

Enabling technologies with a potential contribution to greenhouse gas [GHG] emissions mitigation

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_climate_change_mitigation_technologies_related_to_transportation: boolean // Does this record describe a study on climate change mitigation technologies related to transportation. This refers to technologies aimed at reducing greenhouse gas emissions from the transport of goods and passengers. This includes road transport, railway transport, aeronautics or air transport, maritime or waterways transport, and enabling technologies with a potential or indirect contribution to GHG emissions mitigation. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-carbon transport,” “clean mobility,” or “transport sector decarbonisation.” Include literature discussing the development, deployment, or effectiveness of such technologies.

Road transport of goods or passengers

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_climate_change_mitigation_technologies_related_to_wastewater_treatment_or_waste_management: boolean // Does this record describe a study on climate change mitigation technologies related to wastewater treatment or waste management. This refers to technologies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions from wastewater and solid waste systems. This includes technologies for wastewater treatment, technologies for solid waste management, and enabling technologies with a potential or indirect contribution to GHG emissions mitigation. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-emission waste treatment,” “methane capture in waste systems,” or “climate-smart sanitation.” Include literature discussing development, application, or effectiveness of these technologies.

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_systems_integrating_technologies_for_power_networks: boolean // Does this record describe a study on systems integrating technologies related to power network operation, communication, or information. This refers to integrated systems that support and optimise the generation, transmission, distribution, management, or use of electrical power through technological, infrastructural, or behavioural means. This includes systems supporting electrical power generation, transmission or distribution, relevant infrastructures, and sustainable or improved human practices. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “smart grids,” “intelligent energy systems,” or “grid-integrated technologies.” Include literature discussing the development, integration, or performance of such systems.

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_accessibility_mobility: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Accessibility Mobility. This refers to strategies and technologies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions from the transport sector by improving how people and goods move. This includes "avoid" strategies (e.g. integrating transport and land-use planning, smart logistics, teleworking, compact cities), "shift" strategies (e.g. shifting from car to cycling, walking, or public transit), and "improve" strategies (e.g. electric two-, three-, and four-wheelers, eco-driving, electric vehicles, smaller lightweight vehicles). Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-carbon mobility,” “transport behaviour change,” or “sustainable transport systems.” Include literature discussing planning, policy, behavioural, or technological interventions related to mobility.

AttributesList.AttributeName: Mode shift from car to cycling walking or public transit
Electric two three and four wheelers

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_buildings: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Buildings. This refers to strategies and technologies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions or improve energy performance in the building sector. This includes interventions such as shelter provision, passive houses or retrofits, adjusting temperature set-points, heat pumps, district heating and cooling, combined heat and power, inverter air conditioning, condensing boilers, incremental insulation options, and energy efficiency appliances. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “building energy efficiency,” “low-carbon buildings,” or “resilient building design.” Include literature discussing design, retrofitting, behavioural measures, or technical solutions in the context of buildings.

AttributesList.AttributeName: Heat pumps district heating and cooling

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_manufactured_products_and_services: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Manufactured Products and Services. This refers to mitigation strategies aimed at reducing emissions through the production, use, and design of manufactured goods and the systems that support them. This includes sectors such as clothing, appliances, and materials, with approaches such as use of long-lasting fabrics, sharing economy models, use of recycled or low-carbon materials, low-carbon fabrics, new manufacturing processes and equipment, and circular economy initiatives such as eco-industrial parks. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-emission consumer goods,” “sustainable manufacturing,” or “product life-cycle mitigation.” Include literature discussing technological, material, or behavioural changes in production and consumption of manufactured products and services.

AttributesList.AttributeName: Recycled materials or low carbon materials
New manufacturing processes and equipment use
Recycled materials or low carbon materials for buildings and infrastructure
New manufacturing processes and equipment use

AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_this_study_related_to_food: boolean // Does this record describe a study on Food. This refers to strategies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions through dietary choices, food system efficiency, and sustainable consumption. This includes nutrition optimisation, aligning calorie intake with daily needs, food waste reduction and reuse, shifting from ruminant meat to other protein sources, use of smaller efficient fridges, and encouraging healthy fresh food over processed food. Recognise broader or indirect references such as “low-carbon diets,” “sustainable nutrition,” or “climate-friendly food systems.” Include literature discussing behavioural, technological, or systemic approaches in the food sector.
